LESSON 1: DEEP LEARNING INTRODUCTION¶

1. Overall introduction¶

Deep learning is a sub-field of Machine learning. But in 5 years recently, Deep learning has have lots of achievements by the two main reasons:

  • Data explosion
  • Hardware development

2. Neural network¶

Inspired by human brain, neural network is an architecture where lots of neurons connected together.

Neurons in neural network are connected to create layers. There are three types:

  • Input layer
  • Hidden layer
  • Output layer

2.1. Layers¶

In simple neural network, there are some types of layers: linear layer, different function in activation layer, dropout layer ...

Linear layer¶

Each neuron in linear layer can be calculate as:
${z}^{(l)}_{i} = \sum_{l(l-1)}^{j=1} {a}^{(l−1)}_{j} ∗ {w}^{(l)}_{ji} + {b}^{(l)}_{i}$
${a}^{(l)}_{i} = \sigma({z}^{(l)}_{i})$
where:
${w}^{m}_{n}$ is the n-th weight of linear operator in layer m-th.
${b}^{m}_{n}$ is the n-th bias of linear operator in layer m-th.
${z}^{m}_{n}$ is the n-th results of linear operator in layer m-th.
${a}^{m}_{n}$ is the output of neuron n-th in layer m-th.

Activation layer: ReLU and Leaky ReLU¶

ReLU stands for Rectified-Linear Unit is an activation function.

One problem of ReLU is vanishing gradient and Leaky ReLU will solve this problem.

ReLU and Leaky ReLu is used in hidden layers in a neural network.

Activation layer: Sigmoid, Softmax and Tanh¶

Sigmoid, Softmax and Tanh are activation function for classification problem, and they are used in the last layer of a neural network.
Sigmoid function get any input value and give an output in range from 0 to 1. This value can be understand as probability.

Like Sigmoid, Softmax give an output in range from 0 to 1. But, while Sigmoid is applied for each neuron in a network independently, Softmax is applied for all neurons in a network.

The difference between Sigmoid and Tanh is range of output value. Tanh give an output in range from -1 to 1.

Dropout layer¶

Dropout layer randomly drop some weights in our network to prevent overfit problem.

2.2. Model feedforward¶

From the input of neural network, we calculate the output value of each neuron each layer until we get the output of neural network. This process called model feedforward.

The output of neural network is call prediction or $\hat{y}$.

2.3. Loss function¶

After calculate the prediction of a neural network, we can use this prediction in loss fucntion. loss fucntion calculate the difference between the output of model and the groundtruth value. The smaller difference, the better model evaluation. The bigger difference, the worse model evaluation.
Total loss value of all samples in the training set is called cost value.
There are several types of loss function for each problem: binary cross-entropy or categorical cross-entropy for classification problem, squared error or absolute error for regression problem ...

4.1. Problem¶

The dataset is shared by House prices prediction from Kaggle.
The dataset contains some features about a house and our mission is to predict the house price base on the features.

Data fields¶

  1. SalePrice: the property's sale price in dollars. This is the target variable that you're trying to predict.
  2. MSSubClass: The building class
  3. MSZoning: The general zoning classification
  4. LotFrontage: Linear feet of street connected to property
  5. LotArea: Lot size in square feet
  6. Street: Type of road access
  7. Alley: Type of alley access
  8. LotShape: General shape of property
  9. LandContour: Flatness of the property
  10. Utilities: Type of utilities available
  11. LotConfig: Lot configuration
  12. LandSlope: Slope of property
  13. Neighborhood: Physical locations within Ames city limits
  14. Condition1: Proximity to main road or railroad
  15. Condition2: Proximity to main road or railroad (if a second is present)
  16. BldgType: Type of dwelling
  17. HouseStyle: Style of dwelling
  18. OverallQual: Overall material and finish quality
  19. OverallCond: Overall condition rating
  20. YearBuilt: Original construction date
  21. YearRemodAdd: Remodel date
  22. RoofStyle: Type of roof
  23. RoofMatl: Roof material
  24. Exterior1st: Exterior covering on house
  25. Exterior2nd: Exterior covering on house (if more than one material)
  26. MasVnrType: Masonry veneer type
  27. MasVnrArea: Masonry veneer area in square feet
  28. ExterQual: Exterior material quality
  29. ExterCond: Present condition of the material on the exterior
  30. Foundation: Type of foundation
  31. BsmtQual: Height of the basement
  32. BsmtCond: General condition of the basement
  33. BsmtExposure: Walkout or garden level basement walls
  34. BsmtFinType1: Quality of basement finished area
  35. BsmtFinSF1: Type 1 finished square feet
  36. BsmtFinType2: Quality of second finished area (if present)
  37. BsmtFinSF2: Type 2 finished square feet
  38. BsmtUnfSF: Unfinished square feet of basement area
  39. TotalBsmtSF: Total square feet of basement area
  40. Heating: Type of heating

  42. CentralAir: Central air conditioning
  43. Electrical: Electrical system
  44. 1stFlrSF: First Floor square feet
  45. 2ndFlrSF: Second floor square feet
  46. LowQualFinSF: Low quality finished square feet (all floors)
  47. GrLivArea: Above grade (ground) living area square feet
  48. BsmtFullBath: Basement full bathrooms
  49. BsmtHalfBath: Basement half bathrooms
  50. FullBath: Full bathrooms above grade
  51. HalfBath: Half baths above grade
  52. Bedroom: Number of bedrooms above basement level
  53. Kitchen: Number of kitchens

  55. TotRmsAbvGrd: Total rooms above grade (does not include bathrooms)
  56. Functional: Home functionality rating
  57. Fireplaces: Number of fireplaces
  58. FireplaceQu: Fireplace quality
  59. GarageType: Garage location
  60. GarageYrBlt: Year garage was built
  61. GarageFinish: Interior finish of the garage
  62. GarageCars: Size of garage in car capacity
  63. GarageArea: Size of garage in square feet
  64. GarageQual: Garage quality
  65. GarageCond: Garage condition
  66. PavedDrive: Paved driveway
  67. WoodDeckSF: Wood deck area in square feet
  68. OpenPorchSF: Open porch area in square feet
  69. EnclosedPorch: Enclosed porch area in square feet
  70. 3SsnPorch: Three season porch area in square feet
  71. ScreenPorch: Screen porch area in square feet
  72. PoolArea: Pool area in square feet
  73. PoolQC: Pool quality
  74. Fence: Fence quality
  75. MiscFeature: Miscellaneous feature not covered in other categories
  76. MiscVal: Value of miscellaneous feature
  77. MoSold: Month Sold
  78. YrSold: Year Sold

  80. SaleCondition: Condition of sale

def show_with_subplot(data, cols):
    subplot_n_cols = 5
    subplot_n_rows = int(len(cols) / subplot_n_cols) + 1

    plt.figure(figsize=(15,12))
    for idx, col in enumerate(cols):
        plt.subplot(subplot_n_rows, subplot_n_cols, idx+1)
        sns.histplot(x=col, data=data)

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
